    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-09-19T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-09-19T14:00:00-05:00" n="931"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d931">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.3394/239: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Neville</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-09-19T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 19, 1936—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>121. Embassy’s No. 177, September 4, 10 a.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Navy Department requests that notification be made in the usual manner to
                        the Japanese Government of the proposed informal visits of the U. S. S. <hi
                            rend="italic">Gold Star</hi> to certain ports in the Japanese Mandated
                        Islands in accordance with the following schedule: Palau, arrive October 27,
                        depart October 29; Truk, arrive November 2, depart November 4; Saipan,
                        arrive November 7, depart November 9.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>In making notification to the Foreign Office please state orally that this
                        Government assumes, in view of the numerous instances of the Japanese
                        Government having expressed its willingness for public vessels of the United
                        States to visit any of the open ports of <pb facs="1087" n="992"
                            xml:id="pg_992"/> the Mandated Islands, that the objection of the
                        Japanese Government to the proposed visits of the <hi rend="italic">Gold
                            Star</hi> at Truk, Palau and Saipan referred to in the Embassy’s
                        telegram above-mentioned was due to the fact that the dates indicated for
                        such proposed visits were inconvenient to the Japanese Government. It is
                        understood that the places named were designated by the Japanese Government
                        as open ports by Ordinance No. 13 of June 1, 1922, and it is further
                        understood that these places are still in the category of open ports.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
